1
00:03:17,586 --> 00:03:18,624
Hello.

2
00:03:35,683 --> 00:03:37,131
How are things?

3
00:03:40,201 --> 00:03:41,530
I see!

4
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:06,100
I was just thinking...

5
00:04:13,890 --> 00:04:15,881
Milk goes in the fridge.

6
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:20,850
That too.

7
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:26,874
Is it Wednesday already.

8
00:04:29,080 --> 00:04:30,514
Been working hard?

9
00:04:30,853 --> 00:04:32,181
What at?

10
00:04:33,400 --> 00:04:34,873
No, there weren't many...

11
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:36,423
- What?
- People.

12
00:04:36,887 --> 00:04:38,146
Coffee's settling.

13
00:04:39,386 --> 00:04:40,823
We've always brewed,
haven't we?

14
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:42,651
So what?

15
00:04:46,285 --> 00:04:48,476
Did you buy apricot marmalade?

16
00:04:48,526 --> 00:04:49,917
What about it?

17
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:51,906
You bought apricot marmalade.

18
00:04:53,165 --> 00:04:54,384
Yes?

19
00:04:54,587 --> 00:04:56,075
For as long as I can remember,

20
00:04:56,126 --> 00:04:58,540
we've always eaten orange marmalade
in this house.

21
00:06:33,488 --> 00:06:35,255
Can I have your name?

22
00:06:35,353 --> 00:06:36,446
Orr.

23
00:06:36,865 --> 00:06:37,993
Or what?

24
00:06:38,470 --> 00:06:39,485
Sorry?

25
00:06:39,587 --> 00:06:40,668
Or what?

26
00:06:41,392 --> 00:06:43,056
Karl-Henrik Orr.

27
00:06:43,156 --> 00:06:45,735
Two first names...
Can I have your surname?

28
00:06:47,064 --> 00:06:48,064
Orr.

29
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:50,497
Or? Or your surname.

30
00:06:50,610 --> 00:06:52,150
My name is Orr.

31
00:06:53,394 --> 00:06:54,723
On can be called Orr...

32
00:06:55,302 --> 00:06:56,518
Or not?

33
00:06:57,271 --> 00:06:59,083
We'll put down Knott.

34
00:06:59,658 --> 00:07:00,658
Not what?

35
00:07:00,943 --> 00:07:02,458
Karl-Henrik Knott.

36
00:07:02,880 --> 00:07:04,653
My name's not Knott either.

37
00:07:05,310 --> 00:07:07,427
Write... You write it.

38
00:08:32,040 --> 00:08:33,056
Wake up!

39
00:08:33,841 --> 00:08:35,251
Can you wake up?

40
00:08:36,654 --> 00:08:38,779
I'm in a bit of a hurry, you see.

41
00:08:39,117 --> 00:08:42,790
It's going to press earlier
than I thought.

42
00:08:43,079 --> 00:08:45,555
We're calling ourselves "Just Then"
instead of "Just Now".

43
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:48,898
Everything is happening so quickly.
We want to be sure it's right.

44
00:08:49,588 --> 00:08:53,539
We at "Just Then" only just found out
that you were "Just Here".

45
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:56,703
Don't ask how,
we never reveal our sources.

46
00:08:58,385 --> 00:09:00,098
I've known your wife
for quite a while.

47
00:09:00,595 --> 00:09:01,665
May.

48
00:09:02,920 --> 00:09:04,671
Shall we get started, then?

49
00:09:20,013 --> 00:09:21,554
My name's Anna-Berit.

50
00:09:21,948 --> 00:09:22,960
Hello!

51
00:09:28,827 --> 00:09:29,905
WHAT for?

52
00:09:33,760 --> 00:09:35,855
Maybe I should explain!

53
00:09:36,733 --> 00:09:38,960
We've just now
started a new series...

54
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:41,948
which is called
"The New Single Man".

55
00:09:42,838 --> 00:09:45,104
There has to be debate
about the single man.

56
00:09:45,287 --> 00:09:47,186
It's been going on in Germany
for ages...

57
00:09:47,252 --> 00:09:49,893
but we're the first
to take it up here.

58
00:09:50,480 --> 00:09:51,622
You and I?

59
00:09:52,809 --> 00:09:54,988
The magazine, "Just Then"!

60
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:58,418
Can't you start
with someone else?

61
00:09:58,543 --> 00:10:00,379
I'll be happy to be interviewed later...

62
00:10:00,816 --> 00:10:03,660
when I've been single a bit longer.

63
00:10:04,365 --> 00:10:06,520
No we have to begin
with the fist reaction.

64
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:12,035
One leaves home
without explanation...

65
00:10:13,821 --> 00:10:17,434
Then without explanation,
a note is found...

66
00:10:17,559 --> 00:10:19,207
telling where one went.

67
00:10:19,586 --> 00:10:20,625
"One"?

68
00:10:20,675 --> 00:10:22,473
Meaning a single man like you.

69
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:27,973
I suggest this is
significant singles' behaviour.

70
00:10:28,095 --> 00:10:31,047
A regular singles' impulse.

71
00:10:31,512 --> 00:10:32,571
And then?

72
00:10:32,621 --> 00:10:35,059
The question is, if one is...

73
00:10:35,527 --> 00:10:37,160
on the way to molding his life...

74
00:10:37,320 --> 00:10:40,961
in a social vacuum...

75
00:10:41,831 --> 00:10:43,775
or a new social scenario.

76
00:10:43,825 --> 00:10:49,151
I think one is about to
launch a whole new social game theory.

77
00:10:49,878 --> 00:10:54,360
Transforming one's role-play

78
00:10:54,440 --> 00:10:59,620
in better communication
with the criterion of truth.

79
00:11:00,640 --> 00:11:01,737
Can I write like that?

80
00:11:02,471 --> 00:11:03,745
Did I say that?

81
00:11:03,795 --> 00:11:05,420
No, but that's what I'm asking.

82
00:11:06,244 --> 00:11:07,806
I don't know what to say.

83
00:11:07,936 --> 00:11:11,220
We'll say that,
as it agrees with May's version.

84
00:11:12,580 --> 00:11:14,349
So she has a version?

85
00:11:15,691 --> 00:11:18,261
Did she mention marmalade?

86
00:11:25,760 --> 00:11:27,417
Has Dad already left?

87
00:11:30,531 --> 00:11:32,566
Wasn't he home last night?

88
00:11:34,274 --> 00:11:35,816
Is he traveling somewhere?

89
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:40,833
You know very well that
he wasn't home last night...

90
00:11:40,883 --> 00:11:42,883
and that he's not
going away anywhere.

91
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:53,219
Oh no!

92
00:11:53,430 --> 00:11:54,766
No what?

93
00:11:55,339 --> 00:11:57,534
I don't think there's another woman.

94
00:11:57,672 --> 00:11:59,289
I'd never believe that.

95
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:02,633
I thought that was what
we always believed.

96
00:12:02,735 --> 00:12:04,063
So what is it?

97
00:12:04,280 --> 00:12:05,406
In front of the children

98
00:12:05,456 --> 00:12:08,469
it's all sweetness and light
between Mummy and Daddy.

99
00:12:11,759 --> 00:12:13,745
Aren't you in a hurry?

100
00:12:13,887 --> 00:12:15,561
What a farce!

101
00:12:28,452 --> 00:12:29,827
Did you want some more?

102
00:12:30,234 --> 00:12:32,015
- What?
- Toast.

103
00:12:32,320 --> 00:12:33,390
No thanks.

104
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:35,573
I thought I'd try the new marmalade.

105
00:12:36,568 --> 00:12:39,630
If you don't get a move on soon,
I'll scream!

106
00:12:40,287 --> 00:12:41,642
A quote from Hemingway...

107
00:12:42,005 --> 00:12:43,080
"All we do is...

108
00:12:43,325 --> 00:12:45,927
play our new records
and try new marmelades."

109
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:47,939
It's impossible Hemingway
could have said that.

110
00:12:48,130 --> 00:12:50,724
He was talking about drinks,
of course.

111
00:12:51,663 --> 00:12:53,251
What's your problem?

112
00:12:53,301 --> 00:12:55,935
Is it just not done,
to quote Hemingway in the morning?

113
00:13:08,399 --> 00:13:11,650
Hi! I was just coming to see you.

114
00:13:11,798 --> 00:13:13,009
I was on my way out.

115
00:13:13,228 --> 00:13:14,611
Come along then!

116
00:13:46,040 --> 00:13:47,986
I forgot something!

117
00:14:23,400 --> 00:14:25,001
I didn't forget anything.

118
00:14:35,307 --> 00:14:36,501
Am I typical?

119
00:14:37,040 --> 00:14:37,982
Of what?

120
00:14:38,033 --> 00:14:39,353
Single behaviour?

121
00:14:39,798 --> 00:14:41,798
I'll ask our experts.

122
00:14:42,218 --> 00:14:45,815
Do single behaviour experts
already exist?

123
00:14:46,482 --> 00:14:49,073
Or has the magazine
called in some Germans?

124
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:55,065
You're defensive.

125
00:14:57,520 --> 00:14:58,520
How?

126
00:15:00,011 --> 00:15:02,300
You're defensive
about the term "single man".

127
00:15:03,800 --> 00:15:05,858
I'm transforming my role-play

128
00:15:05,956 --> 00:15:08,096
but protecting myself
at the same time.

129
00:15:09,530 --> 00:15:11,046
Are you trying to be funny?

130
00:15:11,995 --> 00:15:13,479
I just wanted to help.

131
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:15,603
You want pictures, too?

132
00:15:15,653 --> 00:15:18,198
Yes, the back of your head,
when you're talking.

133
00:15:18,651 --> 00:15:19,956
The back of it?

134
00:15:20,080 --> 00:15:23,120
You must stay anonymous.

135
00:15:25,680 --> 00:15:27,074
Where are you going?

136
00:15:27,124 --> 00:15:29,315
I'm not going anywhere!

137
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:35,456
Maybe I have no desire at all
to be just an anonymous single man!

138
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:42,319
Maybe I am defensive...

139
00:15:43,862 --> 00:15:45,995
but why do I have to
be anonymous?

140
00:15:46,870 --> 00:15:48,874
You should think about your family, too.

141
00:15:51,756 --> 00:15:53,818
Alright... back of my head.

142
00:15:59,535 --> 00:16:00,701
So...

143
00:16:02,440 --> 00:16:03,993
- Is this alright?
- It's fine.

144
00:16:04,198 --> 00:16:06,566
If you could just lean
to the left...

145
00:16:07,680 --> 00:16:10,629
Turn your face a little more
towards me.

146
00:16:11,848 --> 00:16:13,785
It doesn't matter
if your cheek shows.

147
00:16:14,016 --> 00:16:16,281
May used to say
that I have soft cheeks.

148
00:16:16,422 --> 00:16:18,374
She wouldn't know me
without soft cheeks.

149
00:16:18,424 --> 00:16:20,042
She knows it's you.

150
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:24,184
But if you want to,
you can turn back your face.

151
00:16:24,571 --> 00:16:26,751
She used to scratch my neck
when I was driving.

152
00:16:26,906 --> 00:16:28,578
But that's a long time ago.

153
00:16:41,240 --> 00:16:44,240
No... Change places.

154
00:16:52,360 --> 00:16:54,089
Don't look so stiff.

155
00:16:54,257 --> 00:16:55,960
I'm trying to look right.

156
00:16:56,505 --> 00:16:58,607
I'm trying to be anonymous
and single.

157
00:16:58,834 --> 00:17:01,170
But everything about me
is associated with something.

158
00:17:01,920 --> 00:17:03,685
You've misunderstood this.

159
00:17:04,674 --> 00:17:05,936
That's maybe typical...

160
00:17:06,233 --> 00:17:08,952
when one has passed
the impulse stage.

161
00:17:14,520 --> 00:17:16,982
Are you trying
to make fun of me?

162
00:17:17,420 --> 00:17:18,873
I'm not really sure.

163
00:17:19,678 --> 00:17:23,045
I feel rather nervous about
being called "the new single man".

164
00:17:25,840 --> 00:17:28,888
Damn it, you've got a great face!

165
00:17:28,938 --> 00:17:31,699
Shame we have to use
the back of your head.

166
00:18:04,750 --> 00:18:06,047
How do I look?

167
00:18:09,360 --> 00:18:10,455
Chic.

168
00:18:10,995 --> 00:18:12,120
How?

169
00:18:12,417 --> 00:18:13,534
What is?

170
00:18:13,640 --> 00:18:14,827
You are.

171
00:18:15,620 --> 00:18:18,503
The dress is.
You, in the dress are.

172
00:18:20,600 --> 00:18:22,478
<i>"For you to know where I am."</i>

173
00:18:24,040 --> 00:18:26,017
I don't understand that.

174
00:18:26,240 --> 00:18:27,693
That was what was on his note.

175
00:18:28,896 --> 00:18:30,982
How would I know where he was?

176
00:18:31,924 --> 00:18:33,736
Thatâ€™s the big question.

177
00:18:34,988 --> 00:18:36,668
That I knew where he was?

178
00:18:37,121 --> 00:18:39,011
Red always works well!

179
00:18:43,440 --> 00:18:46,199
- Do you want to look at something else?
- No, this is good.

180
00:18:50,925 --> 00:18:52,574
Am I still chic?

181
00:18:59,769 --> 00:19:01,441
Because in that case...

182
00:19:16,920 --> 00:19:18,527
Coffee or tea?

183
00:19:18,847 --> 00:19:20,128
Coffee.

184
00:19:20,787 --> 00:19:22,320
Anything else?

185
00:19:22,613 --> 00:19:24,668
Orange juice...

186
00:19:25,082 --> 00:19:26,355
and toast.

187
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:29,324
2 boiled eggs - 4 minutes.

188
00:19:30,827 --> 00:19:31,827
Cheese?

189
00:19:32,121 --> 00:19:33,816
Yes, but nothing two strong.

190
00:19:35,083 --> 00:19:36,457
Marmalade?

191
00:19:38,976 --> 00:19:40,386
Marmalade?

192
00:19:42,425 --> 00:19:44,560
I can bring it anyway.

193
00:19:44,610 --> 00:19:46,066
No marmalade!

194
00:19:46,393 --> 00:19:47,953
Tea with cream and sugar...

195
00:19:48,510 --> 00:19:50,056
and grapefruit juice...

196
00:19:50,600 --> 00:19:52,584
one fried egg, well done...

197
00:19:53,385 --> 00:19:55,424
and two Danish pastries
with strong cheese.

198
00:19:56,520 --> 00:19:58,646
- Instead of the other one?
- Yes.

199
00:19:58,885 --> 00:20:00,791
And 2 Danish pastries
with cheese?

200
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:02,600
Strong.

201
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:08,829
Hi, sweetie!

202
00:20:09,728 --> 00:20:11,981
- How are you?
- Fine.

203
00:20:20,666 --> 00:20:22,849
Has Dad gone away for good?

204
00:20:23,339 --> 00:20:25,026
Why would you think that?

205
00:20:25,448 --> 00:20:27,018
I see you've bought
a new dress...

206
00:20:28,281 --> 00:20:30,047
What's that got to do with it?

207
00:20:30,938 --> 00:20:32,860
I don't know if he's coming back.

208
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:37,235
He could have said something
or wrote something... or called...

209
00:20:37,742 --> 00:20:39,520
or phoned you.

210
00:20:39,633 --> 00:20:43,504
Well, as a matter of fact
he did leave a note.

211
00:20:43,815 --> 00:20:45,418
So he's a nice guy.

212
00:20:45,680 --> 00:20:47,573
Go wandering off
and then come back...!

213
00:20:47,797 --> 00:20:50,276
Anyone would think
I was an armchair.

214
00:20:52,280 --> 00:20:56,000
He gets up and sits down
and gets up and sits down.

215
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:57,541
What the hell is it all about?

216
00:20:57,591 --> 00:20:59,979
You were brought up
in armchairs.

217
00:21:01,353 --> 00:21:03,963
Grandpa and grandma
were very liberal.

218
00:21:07,687 --> 00:21:09,968
And you and Dad
are so damned uptight.

219
00:21:10,156 --> 00:21:11,633
Don't try with me, anyway!

220
00:21:11,844 --> 00:21:14,286
We're not trying anything
at all with you.

221
00:21:14,585 --> 00:21:16,417
But when you say

222
00:21:16,467 --> 00:21:18,866
"Grandma and grandpa
were very liberal people"

223
00:21:18,976 --> 00:21:20,680
as if it were nasty.

224
00:21:20,897 --> 00:21:24,040
What on earth was nasty
about that?

225
00:21:24,304 --> 00:21:27,170
You say so many
things I don't like.

226
00:21:27,358 --> 00:21:30,640
It would be better hear that Grandma
and Grandpa made eyes at each other.

227
00:21:30,800 --> 00:21:32,642
That certainly did not happen.

228
00:21:32,792 --> 00:21:36,238
Anything would be better to hear
than what you fucking say about them!

229
00:21:38,602 --> 00:21:40,534
You've started swearing a lot.

230
00:21:44,984 --> 00:21:46,422
Because I can.

231
00:21:46,738 --> 00:21:49,316
What's a little swearword compared
to the way you answer me?

232
00:21:49,649 --> 00:21:53,065
It's lucky I swore... it gave you
a reason to talk back to me.

233
00:21:53,760 --> 00:21:59,253
What really is my radical-socialist-
liberal-moderate mother all about?

234
00:21:59,566 --> 00:22:01,018
Is that supposed to be funny?

235
00:22:01,088 --> 00:22:03,234
You always comment about
how I speak...

236
00:22:03,408 --> 00:22:05,142
but never about what I say.

237
00:22:05,517 --> 00:22:07,712
One has to be totally
drawing-room-polite.

238
00:22:27,753 --> 00:22:30,708
I promise you'll get to see
all the material.

239
00:22:31,155 --> 00:22:32,782
The material...?

240
00:22:39,600 --> 00:22:41,198
What's your opinion?

241
00:22:46,748 --> 00:22:49,065
I was as careful as possible.

242
00:22:57,920 --> 00:23:01,784
If there's something you'd like
to change, can we discuss it.

243
00:23:11,520 --> 00:23:12,836
That isn't everything...

244
00:23:12,886 --> 00:23:14,971
There are others,
apart from you.

245
00:23:23,578 --> 00:23:24,635
Well?

246
00:23:27,040 --> 00:23:28,776
I'm already stuck.

247
00:23:30,221 --> 00:23:32,085
I barely made it out the door.

248
00:23:33,436 --> 00:23:35,444
What do you mean?

249
00:23:45,023 --> 00:23:46,366
What's this?

250
00:23:46,618 --> 00:23:48,633
Should everyone in
the publishing house find out

251
00:23:48,704 --> 00:23:51,485
that my husband is
"The New Single Man"?

252
00:23:57,600 --> 00:23:59,741
It doesn't matter at all.

253
00:24:01,553 --> 00:24:04,519
I assume
that "single man" means...

254
00:24:04,569 --> 00:24:09,803
that I can notify the university
that he is either sick, or well.

255
00:24:10,320 --> 00:24:13,295
Both can be reason enough
to withdraw from teaching.

256
00:24:15,680 --> 00:24:17,813
But I think you've abused a trust...

257
00:24:17,863 --> 00:24:21,053
if you want to get
any sort of reaction,

258
00:24:21,163 --> 00:24:23,245
which I guess you do.

259
00:24:23,936 --> 00:24:25,839
What a conventional reaction!

260
00:24:26,830 --> 00:24:28,470
Yes, that's possible.

261
00:24:29,260 --> 00:24:33,783
You can interpret Karl-Henrik's behavior
from a conventional point of view

262
00:24:34,204 --> 00:24:36,041
But from that,
we learn nothing...

263
00:24:36,705 --> 00:24:38,806
It only reinforces
our prejudices.

264
00:24:40,595 --> 00:24:43,416
What does that have to do
with your articles?

265
00:24:46,377 --> 00:24:48,869
I think I've been a help.

266
00:24:49,920 --> 00:24:53,861
People look at you and Karl-Henrik
in a warm and sympathetic way.

267
00:24:55,811 --> 00:24:57,357
Didn't they before?

268
00:24:58,478 --> 00:25:02,322
Other people's tolerance
threshold is lower.

